  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theory—it's something I've seen play out in my own life and around me. As a delivery driver in Chicago with a high school diploma and a curious mind, I've noticed how people, especially young kids, get nervous when they're told they're 'not good at math' or 'not smart enough for science.' It's not about being bad at the subject—it's about the fear of confirming a stereotype. When someone hears they're 'not a STEM person,' their brain starts to shut down, and that's when they lose interest or confidence. I remember when my son was in school, he'd avoid math problems because he thought he wasn't 'the type' for it. That's stereotype threat in action. We should address it, but not with big, complicated programs. Start small: encourage kids to try things without judgment, help them see that everyone learns at their own pace, and remind them that being 'good at STEM' isn't about being a genius—it's about showing up and trying. In my community, where people often don't have much access to advanced education, this kind of mindset shift can make all the difference. It's not about fixing people—it's about creating space where they feel safe to try without fear of failure. And honestly, as someone who's never been in a classroom but still has a deep curiosity about how things work, I believe that's the most important thing: letting people know they belong in STEM, no matter where they start.",
